    "what_description": "Symphytum officinale is a perennial herb native to Europe, Western Asia, and North Africa. It belongs to the family Boraginaceae, commonly known as the borage family. This plant grows to a height of 1-3 meters, with a stout stem, lanceolate leaves that are 10-20 cm long and 2-5 cm wide, and blue or purple flowers that are 5-7 mm in diameter and arranged in a raceme. The leaves and stems of Symphytum officinale contain mucilage, which is a complex mixture of polysaccharides and glycoproteins that give the plant its medicinal properties. The plant's roots and leaves have been used in traditional medicine for centuries to treat various ailments, including wounds, inflammation, and respiratory conditions.",
