    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Symphytum officinale are tincture, infusion, salve, ointment, and tea, which are derived from the plant's leaves and roots. Tincture is a concentrated liquid extract used for internal consumption, typically taken sublingually or added to food and drinks. Infusion, also known as herbal tea, involves steeping the dried leaves in hot water to produce a soothing drink. Topical preparations, such as salve and ointment, are made by mixing the plant's extract with a carrier oil or other ingredients to create a healing balm for skin conditions like eczema and burns. These preparations are used to leverage the plant's anti-inflammatory, antiseptic, and soothing properties, which are attributed to its high concentration of mucilages and other bioactive compounds.",
